Certainly! When handling sensitive data like a credit card number, it's crucial to apply strong validation to ensure security and compliance with best practices. Here’s an example of an HTML form that includes an input field for a credit card number with various validations:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Credit Card Form</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
        }
        .error {
            color: red;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h2>Credit Card Information</h2>
    <form action="/submit.php" method="post" onsubmit="return validateForm()">
        <div>
            <label for="cardNumber">Credit Card Number:</label>
            <input type="text" id="cardNumber" name="cardNumber" placeholder="Enter Credit Card Number" required pattern="\d{16}">
            <span class="error" id="cardNumberError"></span>
        </div>
        <div>
            <label for="cvv">CVV:</label>
            <input type="text" id="cvv" name="cvv" placeholder="Enter CVV" required pattern="\d{3}">
            <span class="error" id="cvvError"></span>
        </div>
        <div>
            <label for="expiryDate">Expiry Date (MM/YY):</label>
            <input type="text" id="expiryDate" name="expiryDate" placeholder="Enter Expiry Date" required pattern="(0[1-9]|1[0-2])\/\d{2}">
            <span class="error" id="expiryDateError"></span>
        </div>
        <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>

    <script>
        function validateForm() {
            const cardNumber = document.getElementById('cardNumber').value;
            const cvv = document.getElementById('cvv').value;
            const expiryDate = document.getElementById('expiryDate').value;

            let isValid = true;

            // Clear previous error messages
            document.getElementById('cardNumberError').textContent = '';
            document.getElementById('cvvError').textContent = '';
            document.getElementById('expiryDateError').textContent = '';

            if (!cardNumber.match(/^\d{16}$/)) {
                document.getElementById('cardNumberError').textContent = 'Invalid Credit Card Number';
                isValid = false;
            }

            if (!cvv.match(/^\d{3}$/)) {
                document.getElementById('cvvError').textContent = 'Invalid CVV';
                isValid = false;
            }

            if (!expiryDate.match(/^(0[1-9]|1[0-2])\/\d{2}$/)) {
                document.getElementById('expiryDateError').textContent = 'Invalid Expiry Date';
                isValid = false;
            }

            return isValid;
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
1. **HTML Structure:**
   - The form includes three main fields: `cardNumber`, `cvv`, and `expiryDate`.
   - Each field has a corresponding `label` and `input` element.
   - The `pattern` attribute is used to enforce specific formats for each field.
   - Error messages are displayed next to each field using `span` elements with the class `error`.

2. **CSS Styling:**
   - Basic styling is added to improve the appearance of the form and error messages.

3. **JavaScript Validation:**
   - The `validateForm` function is called when the form is submitted.
   - It checks the validity of each field based on the `pattern` attribute and displays appropriate error messages if the input is invalid.
   - The function returns `true` only if all fields are valid, preventing the form from submitting otherwise.

This example ensures that the credit card number, CVV, and expiry date are formatted correctly and provides immediate feedback to the user if they enter invalid data.

